05843nam a22008055i 9781503613904DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020008446  a97815036139047 a10.1515/97815036139042doi  a(DE-B1597)573881  a(OCoLC)1224277983  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHD31.2b.R685 2020 4aHD31.2b.R685 2020eb 7aBUS0410002bisacsh04a303.3/82231 aRoulet, Thomas J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Power of Being Divisive :bUnderstanding Negative Social Evaluations /cThomas J. Roulet. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface: The Relevance of Negative Social Evaluations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: A Framework to Understand Negative Social Evaluations -- tChapter 1. Where It All Begins: Understanding the Antecedents of Negative Social Evaluations -- tChapter 2. Resisting Hostility: Resilience to Negative Social Evaluations -- tChapter 3. Going Beyond Resilience and Capitalizing on Negative Social Evaluations -- tChapter 4. Practical Implications for Individuals, Organizations, and Society -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last decade, research on negative social evaluations, from adverse reputation to extreme stigmatization, has burgeoned both at the individual and organizational level. Thus far, this research has largely focused on major corporate risks. Corporate public relations and business executives intuitively know that a negative image deters important relationships—from customers and partners, to applicants, stakeholders, and potential funding. At the same time, business is conducted in an age of heightened connection, including digital platforms for criticism and a 24-hour news cycle. Executives know that some degree of public disapproval is increasingly unavoidable. Negative social evaluations can also put social actors on the map. In the era of identity politics, many political leaders express controversial views to appeal to specific audiences and gain in popularity. Through network and signaling effects, being controversial can potentially pay off. Thomas J. Roulet offers a framework for understanding not only how individuals and organizations can survive in an age of increasing scrutiny, but how negative social evaluations can surprisingly yield positive results. A growing body of work has begun to show that being "up against the rest" is an active driver of corporate identity, and that firms that face strong public hostility can benefit from internal bonding. Synthesizing this work with his original research, and drawing comparisons to work on misconduct and scandals, Roulet addresses an important gap by providing a broader perspective to link the antecedents and consequences of negative social evaluations. Moreover, he reveals the key role that audiences play in assessing these consequences, whether positive or negative, and the crucial function of media in establishing conditions in which public disapproval can bring positive results. Examples and cases cover Uber and Google, Monsanto, Electronic Arts, and the investment banking industry during the financial crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aBusiness enterprisesxPublic opinion. 0aEvaluationxSocial aspects. 0aIndustriesxPublic opinion. 0aManagement. 0aOccupationsxPublic opinion. 0aStigma (Social psychology) 0aStigma (Social psychology). 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Management.2bisacsh  aControversy.  aDisapproval.  aEthics.  aMisconduct.  aNegative social